fter metadata generation, retest, `generateLibraryStats`, and a commit for the library iteration succeed.\n./forge/docs/native-test-verification.md:67:  Gradle log (`generateMetadata`, `test`, or `runNativeTraceImage`).\n./forge/docs/dynamic-access-workflow.md:252:    Keep -- yes --> KeepOK([Phase returns ok=true,<br/>keep generated tests])\n./forge/docs/dynamic-access-workflow.md:274:    GenMD[generateMetadata] --> Test{./gradlew test passes?}\n./forge/docs/dynamic-access-workflow.md:315:| Reachability-repo Gradle tasks | `scaffold`, `populateArtifactURLs`, `generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport`, `test`, `nativeTest`, `generateMetadata`, `generateLibraryStats`. |\n./forge/benchmarks/benchmark_runner.py:70:            \"Forwarded to add_new_library_support.py. Keeps generated tests for dynamic-access strategies \"\n./forge/git_scripts/make_pr_new_library_support.py:108:        \"paths are explained by the generated reachability metadata.\"\n./forge/git_scripts/make_pr_new_library_support.py:114:    \"\"\"Load covered dynamic-access call sites and generated metadata rules for PR evidence.\"\"\"\n./forge/prompt_templates/initial/basic_initial.md:4:You need to generate comprehensive tests for the library defined by these Maven coordinates: {library}.\n./forge/prompt_templates/initial/basic_initial.md:19:- When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally requires open-ended dynamic class loading that Native Image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, catch `Error`, verify it with `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`, and re-throw if it does not match. This proves Native Image fails for the right reason instead of skipping the test.\n./forge/prompt_templates/persistent/default_agent_rules.md:4:- Keep generated tests meaningful and avoid replacing real coverage with trivial assertions.\n./forge/prompt_templates/persistent/dynamic_access_rules.md:4:- Maintain a one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and generated test class files.\n./forge/prompt_templates/persistent/dynamic_access_rules.md:17:- When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally requires open-ended dynamic class loading that Native Image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, catch `Error`, verify it with `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`, and re-throw if it does not match. This proves Native Image fails for the right reason instead of skipping the test.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:89:- Iteratively generate a meaningful, cohesive JUnit test suite for library using AI.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:123:- `--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access` keeps generated tests for dynamic-access workflows even if no dynamic-access call sites are covered.\n./forge/DEVELOPING.md:418:The `dynamic_access_iterative` workflow improves metadata accuracy by using the `generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport` Gradle task to identify which dynamic-access call sites (reflection, JNI, resources, serialization) are not yet covered by the generated tests. Instead of generating tests blindly, the workflow iterates class-by-class, sending the agent targeted prompts with the exact uncovered call sites for each class. After each attempt, the report is regenerated and coverage deltas are computed to decide whether to retry the same class or move on.\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py:122:        generated_metadata_file = os.path.join(\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py:130:        if not os.path.isfile(generated_metadata_file):\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py:133:                f\"{generated_metadata_file}. Skipping Codex metadata repair.\",\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/workflow_strategy.py:37:    (e.g. scaffold a library, generate metadata, run tests, iterate on fixes).\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/workflow_strategy.py:391:        log_stage(\"generate-metadata\", f\"Running generateMetadata for {self.library}\")\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/dynamic_access_iterative_strategy.py:159:                    self._print_dynamic_access_message(\"Coverage not improved. Keeping generated tests by request.\")\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/dynamic_access_iterative_strategy.py:625:        \"\"\"Capture tracked and untracked changes under the generated library test tree.\"\"\"\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/basic_iterative_strategy.py:16:    │   https://github.com/oracle/graalvm-reachability-metadata/blob/master/docs/CONTRIBUTING.md#generate-metadata-and-test   │\n./forge/ai_workflows/workflow_strategies/basic_iterative_strategy.py:198:                        f\"Checkpoint generated tests for {self.library} ({unittest_number})\"\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_post_generation_pi.py:53:            \"   or an unsupported platform feature), remove the generated test that causes that failure.\",\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_post_generation_pi.py:54:            \"   You may also remove generated test-only files that are only needed by that failing test.\",\n./forge/ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py:81:            \"Iteratively generate and validate unit tests for a given library using the configured agent.\\n\\n\"\n./forge/ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py:144:            \"When using dynamic-access strategies, keep generated tests even when they do not improve \"\n./forge/ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py:567:            log_stage(\"generate-metadata\", f\"Benchmark mode: running generateMetadata and generateLibraryStats for {library}\")\n./docs/CONTRIBUTING.md:39:- generate metadata and store it in the proper location\n./docs/CONTRIBUTING.md:42:If you already have the test project structure in this repository and need to generate or regenerate metadata, use the `generateMetadata` task:\n./docs/CONTRIBUTING.md:74:Use the `scaffold` task to generate metadata and test stubs:\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:22:| **Repository automation (Metadata Forge)** | Generate or repair metadata using LLM-driven pipelines. | Per coordinate, the toolkit can: (1) **add support for a new library** — generate a JUnit / Kotlin / Scala test suite, scaffold metadata, and iterate until JVM-mode tests pass and dynamic-access is collected ([`add_new_library_support.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py)); (2) **fix a Java compilation (`javac`) failure** raised by a library version bump ([`fix_javac_fail.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_javac_fail.py)); (3) **fix a JVM-mode (`javaTest`) runtime failure** raised by a version bump ([`fix_java_run_fail.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_java_run_fail.py)); (4) **fix a `native-image` runtime failure** raised by a version bump ([`fix_ni_run.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py)); (5) **improve dynamic-access coverage** of already-supported libraries by targeting uncovered call sites; (6) **post-generation repair** of the metadata produced by a previous run ([`fix_post_generation_pi.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_post_generation_pi.py), [`fix_metadata_codex.py`](../forge/ai_workflows/fix_metadata_codex.py)). Each task runs Gradle tasks against a worktree of this repo, appends a schema-validated metrics record, and — when invoked through [`forge/git_scripts/make_pr_*.py`](../forge/git_scripts/) — opens a PR for human review. See [forge/docs/architecture.md](../forge/docs/architecture.md). |\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:84:1. **Add new library support** — generate a JUnit test suite, scaffold metadata, iterate until JVM-mode tests pass and dynamic-access metadata is collected.\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:114:| `human-intervention` | Issue / PR | Automation could not safely complete the work without manual follow-up, or automated PR review requested changes. |\n./docs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:115:| `human-intervention-fixed` | PR | Manual follow-up has fixed a PR previously requiring intervention; review automation may approve and merge it after merge gates pass. |\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:2:When the repository doesn’t have reachability metadata for a library you are using, the easiest way to generate it is to execute the test suite of the library with the Native Image Agent enabled. The agent is installed together with native-image and can be used to identify elements used during application execution that cannot be discovered by static analysis.\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:26:To run the test task with the agent, run `./gradlew -Pagent` test. This will generate metadata in the build output directory of the project (under `build/native/agent/test`).\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:59:Conditional metadata can be generated by inserting the Native Image Agent options into the command line of the JVM that runs the tests.\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:73:native-image-configure generate-conditional --user-code-filter=user-code-filter.json --class-name-filter=extra-code-filter.json --input-dir=<agent-output-dir> --input-dir=<agent-output-dir-2>... --output-dir=final-metadata/\n./docs/CollectingMetadata.md:80:The best thing for the community is to include the generated metadata and build file changes into the library itself. Before creating a PR to the library:\n./docs/CI.md:25:  - Uses: generateMatrixBatchedCoordinates to build a matrix (java + os). Runs full tests, pulls only allowed Docker images, then disables Docker networking for deterministic runs.\n./docs/CI.md:28:  - Uses: [`generateChangedMetadataTestMatrix`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) with base/head SHAs to test only what changed. It batches each changed metadata version's [`tested-versions`](../metadata/com.google.protobuf/protobuf-java-util/index.json) into chunks of up to 30 versions per job, then pulls allowed images, disables Docker networking, validates config, and runs only that batch.\n./docs/CI.md:31:  - Uses: [`generateChangedTestedVersionsMatrix`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) to compute only newly added [`tested-versions`](../metadata/com.google.protobuf/protobuf-java-util/index.json) from the base/head diff and pairs them with the matching [`metadata-version`](../metadata/com.google.protobuf/protobuf-java-util/index.json), then runs [`run-consecutive-tests.sh`](../.github/workflows/scripts/run-consecutive-tests.sh) only for those added versions.\n./docs/CI.md:34:  - Uses: generateInfrastructureChangedCoordinatesMatrix. Pulls allowed images, disables Docker networking, validates config, then runs tests.\n./docs/CI.md:37:  - Uses: generateAffectedSpringTestMatrix to compute impacted Spring AOT projects and produce a matrix; runs triaged native tests via [.github/workflows/scripts/run-spring-aot-triaged-test.sh](../.github/workflows/scripts/run-spring-aot-triaged-test.sh).\n./docs/CI.md:43:  - Uses: [`fetchExistingLibrariesWithNewerVersions`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) plus [`generateNewLibraryVersionCompatibilityMatrix`](../tests/tck-build-logic/src/main/groovy/org.graalvm.internal.tck-harness.gradle) to build a [`ci.json`](../ci.json)-driven matrix. The matrix generator limits the number of libraries per run, limits each library to at most 30 newer versions per run before expanding across the configured GraalVM JDK/OS combinations, records tested versions only after they pass on every required environment, and creates a single aggregated failure issue per failed library version while preserving the prior failure issue format with added OS and JDK lines.\n./docs/CI.md:49:- [.github/workflows/publish-scheduled-coverage.yml](../.github/workflows/publish-scheduled-coverage.yml): scheduled/manual workflow that generates repository coverage badges and the coverage dashboard from exploded stats files under [stats/](../stats/) and repository [metadata/**/index.json](../metadata/), then force-pushes the published artifacts to the `stats/coverage` branch. The published branch only keeps `latest/badges.json`, `latest/metrics-over-time.svg`, `latest/metrics-over-time-dark.svg`, and `history/history.json`.\n./build.gradle:262:    t.setDescription(\"Determines one artifact coordinate via generateInfrastructureChangedCoordinatesMatrix (or uses -Pcoordinate/-Pcoordinates if provided), then runs testInfra for that coordinate and also for 1/64. Options: -Pparallelism to control concurrency.\")\n./build.gradle:594:        println(\"Verified generated metadata for ${coordinate}: ${versionDir}\")\n./tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-daemon-embeddable/2.3.20/build.gradle:12:File generatedTestResourcesDir = layout.buildDirectory.dir(\"generated/test-resources\").get().asFile\n./tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-stdlib-jdk7/1.5.31/src/test/kotlin/org_jetbrains_kotlin/kotlin_stdlib_jdk7/Kotlin_stdlib_jdk7Test.kt:139:            val generatedFile: JdkPath = createTempFile(generatedDirectory, \"metadata-\", \".json\")\n./tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-stdlib-jdk7/1.5.31/src/test/kotlin/org_jetbrains_kotlin/kotlin_stdlib_jdk7/Kotlin_stdlib_jdk7Test.kt:149:            assertThat(generatedFile.name).startsWith(\"metadata-\").endsWith(\".json\")\n./tests/src/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.4.1/README.md:4:./generate-metadata.sh\n./tests/src/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.4.1/README.md:7:The generated metadata can be found in the `build/native/agent-output/test` directory.\n./tests/src/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.4.1/build.gradle:22:\t\t// replace typeReachable value for entries generated by LogbackTests test class\n./tests/src/org.liquibase/liquibase-core/5.0.1/README.md:4:./generate-metadata.sh\n./tests/src/org.liquibase/liquibase-core/5.0.1/README.md:7:The generated metadata can be found in the `build/native/agent-output/test` directory.\n./tests/src/org.liquibase/liquibase-core/5.0.1/README.md:9:Afterwards, the generated metadata has been cleaned:\n./COVERAGE.md:18:| [`biz.aQute.bnd:biz.aQute.bnd.annotation`](https://github.com/bndtools/bnd) | 6.4.1 | 100.0% (9/9 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> The biz.aQute.bnd.annotation artifact provides bnd-specific Java annotations for OSGi bundle metadata, package versioning, capabilities, service metadata, JPMS hints, licenses, and plugin declarations. These annotations are consumed by bnd and related tooling to generate or validate bundle headers and metadata without hard-coding that information in build instructions.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:126:| [`com.thoughtworks.paranamer:paranamer`](https://github.com/paul-hammant/paranamer) | 2.3<br>– 2.8.3 | 100% (0/0 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> ParaNamer is a Java library that exposes constructor and method parameter names at runtime. It can read parameter names from generated metadata, annotations, debug symbols, or bytecode so frameworks can bind arguments without manual name declarations.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:149:| [`dev.zio:zio-internal-macros_3`](https://github.com/zio/zio) | 2.1.19 | 100% (0/0 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> zio-internal-macros provides internal Scala 3 support classes used by ZIO macros to render layer wiring diagnostics and ANSI-formatted compile-time messages. It is a small ZIO implementation artifact rather than a public end-user API, and it supports macro-generated errors for ZIO layer provisioning and test/spec wiring.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:326:| [`org.apache.arrow:arrow-format`](https://github.com/apache/arrow) | 7.0.0<br>– 19.0.0 | 100% (0/0 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Apache Arrow Format provides generated Java classes for Apache Arrow IPC FlatBuffer metadata definitions. It lets Java applications work with the schema, record batch, dictionary batch, and message structures used by Arrow's columnar interchange format.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:377:| [`org.apache.parquet:parquet-format-structures`](https://github.com/apache/parquet-java) | 1.12.2<br>– 1.12.3 | 100.0% (2/2 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Apache Parquet Format Structures provides Java classes used by parquet-mr to work with the parquet-format Thrift structures. It packages generated model code for Parquet schema and metadata structures so Parquet Java components can read and write the format consistently.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:538:| [`org.junit.platform:junit-platform-reporting`](https://github.com/junit-team/junit-framework) | 1.9.2 | 100% (0/0 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> JUnit Platform Reporting provides listeners and XML writers for legacy and Open Test Reporting formats. It is used by JUnit Platform launchers and native test integrations to generate test execution reports.</details> |\n./COVERAGE.md:602:| [`org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-configuration-processor`](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot) | 2.7.18<br>– 3.3.13 | 100% (0/0 calls) | <details><summary>Show</summary> Spring Boot Configuration Processor is a compile-time Java annotation processor that generates configuration metadata from Spring Boot configuration property classes. The generated metadata helps IDEs and other tools provide contextual documentation, validation hints, and property completion for Spring Boot application configuration.</details> |\n./skills/review-library-bulk-update/SKILL.md:15:- Close the PR when it contains unrelated changes such as workflow files, Gradle files, generated sources, or test code that clearly did not belong in a bulk version update.\n./skills/review-library-bulk-update/SKILL.md:24:   - Read the body and verify it is a bot-generated \"Added tested versions\" summary.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:16:- Expect runtime-focused changes plus the normal generated support files for the newly tested version: test source updates, dependency adjustments, runtime configuration, a new metadata-version directory, stats, and metadata index changes.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Native-image execution should remain enabled by default when the repaired test reaches the native lane. Do not accept changes that skip or short-circuit native-image behavior. When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading that native image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, accept the `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` catch pattern from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`. Reject raw native-only skips, bare `catch (Error)` blocks, and use of this pattern for ordinary reflection, resources, serialization, dynamic proxies, JNI, or missing reachability metadata.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:42:   - Treat generated test project files such as `.gitignore`, `build.gradle`, `gradle.properties`, `settings.gradle`, and `user-code-filter.json` as normal when they live under the target version's test directory.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:45:   - Reject legacy native-image metadata config files. Metadata for generated support and test-only metadata must use `reachability-metadata.json`.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:19:- Tests should execute under native image by default. Do not accept tests that disable themselves under native image. When a test exercises behavior that fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading that native image cannot support, such as loading classes, JARs, generated bytecode, plugin implementations, or other class definitions that are only discovered after the native executable is built, accept the `NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(e)` catch pattern from `org.graalvm.internal.tck`. Reject raw native-only skips, bare `catch (Error)` blocks, and use of this pattern for ordinary reflection, resources, serialization, dynamic proxies, JNI, or missing reachability metadata.\n./skills/review-library-new-request/SKILL.md:42:   - Be suspicious of changes to build logic, workflows, unrelated libraries, generated sources outside the target test directory, or wide refactors.\n./skills/README.md:44:### `close-human-intervention-and-failing-ci-prs`\n./skills/README.md:46:Closes batches of open pull requests that have the `human-intervention` label or failing CI.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:23:- Prefer concrete evidence from native run output, generated metadata, stats, and CI over style objections.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:40:   - Treat generated test project files such as `.gitignore`, `build.gradle`, `gradle.properties`, `settings.gradle`, and `user-code-filter.json` as normal when they live under the target version's test directory.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:44:   - Reject legacy native-image metadata config files. Metadata for generated support and test-only metadata must use `reachability-metadata.json`.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:49:   - Metadata additions should be specific enough to the target library behavior; do not require hand-minimized entries when generated metadata is coherent and validation passes.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/close-human-intervention-and-failing-ci-prs/SKILL.md:2:name: close-human-intervention-and-failing-ci-prs\n./skills/close-human-intervention-and-failing-ci-prs/SKILL.md:3:description: Close batches of 